f his examples from major wars involving Western militaries. They include British soldiers in the trenches of World War I, U.S. pilots in World War II, and U.S. Marines in Iraq and Afghanistan. Hassner shows that even modern, rational, and bureaucratized military organizations have taken-and must take-religious practice into account in the conduct of war.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aSoldiersxReligious life. 0aWarxReligious aspects. 4aMilitary History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Security (National & International).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCOR eBook-Package 2016z978311066749308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCOR eBook-Package Pilot Project 2016z978311066589508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell Univ. Press eBook-Package Pilot Project 2016-2017z978311060673740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501703690423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501703690.jpg  a978-3-11-060673-7  Cornell Univ. Press eBook-Package Pilot Project 2016-2017c2016d2017  a978-3-11-066589-5  COR eBook-Package Pilot Project 2016  a978-3-11-066749-3  COR eBook-Package 2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles